values.text:
Students are welcome to park at any of the parking lots at San Jacinto College, with the exception of those that are specifically marked for Employees or Visitors. All vehicles parked on college property are required to be registered and display a San Jacinto College parking permit unless the driver is a visitor with legitimate business at a campus. Parking decals are available at any campus business office.

They include Grade Appeals, General Complaints, Discrimination and Harassment complaints (excludes sexual harassment and sexual misconduct) and Complaints Alleging Sexual Harassment, Sexual Assault, Dating Violence, Domestic Violence, Intimate Partner Violence And Stalking.

values.text:
Oh no :(... We would hate to see you go! Drop Deadline Dates can be found here.

To drop a course online:
1. Go to the SOS login
2. To login: enter your Student ID number (capital G with the assigned eight digit number).
3. Enter your SOS password.
4. Select My Registration and follow the system prompts.
5. Select your desired registration term.
6. Select Step 5, Register for Classes, and select “drop” for desired classes under drop down box.
7. Select Submit Changes to save the request or to determine if there are registration restrictions.
8. When the schedule is correct, select the View My Schedule link at the bottom of the page to confirm your action.

dialog_nodes.title: Step 3 - Submit Required Documentation for Appeal Committee

values:
Step 3: Submit required documentation for appeal committee review

Your appeal packet will be collected and forwarded to the appeal committee for further review. Appeal decisions will be emailed to you before the next scheduled meeting at your SJC student address. Appeals must be submitted no later than one week prior to the appeal meeting date. Please be prepared to pay for your registration expenses (tuition, fees, books and supplies) since your appeal might not be reviewed prior to the payment deadline.

If you submitted an appeal for review by the committee, please click on the Financial Aid Appeals link and look under the Appeal Committee Meeting Dates section to determine when your appeal will be reviewed.

values.text: Dual Credit is a form of concurrent enrollment allowing a student to take certain courses at San Jacinto College that earn both college and high school credit. Typically, students take two courses each semester while in high school. By doing this, students can graduate from high school with 24+ hours of college credit! You can earn even more by taking summer courses.

generic.title: Would you like more assistance with Dual Credit?

dialog_nodes.title: Option 3 - Steps to Apply & Register for Dual Credit

values.text:
After receiving approval from your high school, you will need to follow the steps below to apply and register for dual credit classes:
1. Apply online and get an SJC Student ID (G-Number).
2. Meet the Texas Success Initiative Assessment (TSIA) requirements.
3. Submit proof of or exemption from Bacterial Meningitis vaccination.
4. Register for classes.
5. Pay for Classes.

generic.title: Would you like more information regarding these steps?

values.text:
What is Open Books?

San Jacinto College is committed to identifying quality instructional materials for our students to help them to achieve their educational goals without unnecessary costs. The Open Books program (also referred to as First Day) is focused on affordable learning and works with faculty to identify quality low or no cost resources for students, which allows them to focus on learning and not the expense of textbooks. Any student that is currently enrolled at San Jacinto College can enroll in an available Open Books course.

generic.title: Would you like to learn more about Open Books?

values.text:
How To Register For Open Book Courses

To find Open Book Courses go to the Course Finder .
1. Select the Term you are interested in
2. Click on Advanced Search Options
3. In the Search Term box enter Open Books
4. Click Search. Open Books classes will display.

If applicable, students are charged the cost of materials at the time of registration. This is itemized on the student fee bill slip. You may log into SOS under “My Registration-Print Options-Schedule/ Fee Bill”.

University students do not need to submit their high school transcript. University students who hold a degree (associate, bachelor’s, master’s or doctoral) only need to submit an official transcript from the school that awarded the highest degree. If you took classes after you earned your degree, we will need a transcript from that college or university as well.
Once your transcript(s) arrive, you’ll need to make an official request to have your transcript(s) evaluated to determine what courses will transfer to San Jacinto College. You can request the evaluation by visiting any campus student services office or by calling 281-998-6150.

dialog_nodes.title: Grades - Appeals

values.text:
If you believe that a final grade is incorrect, you may appeal the final grade received in the course.

• Start appeal as soon as possible following the receipt of the grade

• Appeal process shall be filed no later than 30 calendar days after the end of the semester

• Appeal process must be resolved within 120 calendar days following the inititation of the appeal

generic.title: Would you like to learn how to start an appeal for a grade change?

dialog_nodes.user_label: How do I appeal my final grade in a course?

dialog_nodes.title: Yes - How to Start an Grade Appeal

values.text: The first step in appealing your final grade is meeting with your instructor. In this meeting, you and the instructor will discuss the grade that you believe is incorrect. During this meeting, only the grades on tests, reports, etc. and the grading system listed in the syllabus will be discussed and recalculated as necessary. Whenever possible, the matter should be resolved at this meeting.

generic.title: Would you like me to continue?

values.text: The College awards a grade of WL for course withdrawals to students who were new first-time-in-college students in fall 2007 or thereafter and are affected by the six-drop limit. The grade of WL is the indicator that this withdrawal is counted in the six drop limit. An affected student is limited to six grades the equivalent of WL from all Texas public colleges and universities combined.

Step 2: As part of our mission in ensuring student success, all students who are new to San Jacinto College will need to meet with an Admissions Advisor to talk about programs available, choose their courses, and potential career options.

If you are not a first-time student, we recommend that you talk with an educational planner if you are unsure about what to do before registering for classes – not just the first time, but for every semester.

An Advisor or Educational Planner can make sure you are progressing correctly through your degree plan, answer your questions and help you decide on changes you might want to make. An Advisor or Educational Planner can also help your determine if a Distance Learning course is right for you.

Sure thing, I can help you with information on the Student Enrollment Responsibility Agreement (SERA). The College is initiating a new process for informing students of the expectations of the College and the students’ responsibility for key areas.

SERA will be a pop-up once an academic year based on the first term that the student initiates the registration process. All students (both credit and non-credit) will need to accept the Student Enrollment Responsibility Agreement (SERA) prior to continuing with their registration process on SOS. This agreement follows the National Association of College and University Business Offices (NACUBO) template and is in use at many institutions across the country.

values.text:
Passport
Your passport must be valid for at least six months from your date of enrollment. Check the expiration date and have it renewed if needed. You can do this in the U.S. through an official consulate from your home country. If you renew through the mail, be sure to request certified delivery with a return receipt.

I-94 Card

When you enter the United States, U.S. Customs and Border Protection has automated Form I-94 at the port of entry. A traveler lawfully admitted (or paroled) into the U.S. may print their lawful record of admission (I-94 form) from the CBP website.

values:
6 Drop Limit Hold

This refers to the Texas state drop limit and applies to students attending college for the first time Fall 2007 or later. Once the drops reach 2 drops remaining, it then becomes an active hold that will prevent registration. You must come in person to meet with an Advisor for registration and/or withdraws from that point forward.

Proof of Meningitis Hold

Please submit your proof of meningitis vaccination by fax to 281-669-4720 or email Meningitis.Docs\@sjcd.edu.

New Student Orientation Hold

If you are a first time college student or have less than 12 college credit hours, New Student Orientation is mandatory. Please log into your SOS account and sign up for the next available New Student Orientation session.

Official Transcript/Updated Transcript Needed Hold

You’ll need to submit your official high school or college transcript to:
• San Jacinto College
• Attn: Student Records Management
• 13735 Beamer Rd.
• Houston, TX 77089

First Time in College Mandatory Advising Hold

Please see an Advisor located in the Admissions Office to complete the first time in college mandatory advising session.

Account Past Due Hold

This means there is a past due amount owed to San Jacinto College. Please log into your SOS account to review the past due amount. You can make payment in SOS or by coming in person to any campus Business Office. Once the past due payment has been made, the Business Office will remove the hold.

Name Change Hold

You’ll need to submit proof of name change in person to the Admissions Office if you are a first time student and to Educational Planning, Counseling and Completion if you are a returning student.

If you were recently married, you can submit the marriage license with photo I.D. or social security card with photo I.D. or passport or court order.

If you were recently divorced, you can submit the divorce decree and photo I.D. or social security card with photo I.D. or passport.

Residency Verification Hold

Please see an advisor or educational planner to verify your current residency designation.

Returned Mail Hold

Please contact the Admissions office to verify you address.

values.text:
Turn your home into your classroom! We've created several ways for you to conveniently grab some of your basic classes - from a distance. You can complete courses online, or you can even take courses that are part on campus and part online.

Just like our traditional college classes, every distance learning course offers full credit, transferability, and it has tests, assignments and an instructor that can help you.

Online Partial (OLP)
Most of the content is delivered through computers and multimedia. These courses use Blackboard, the San Jacinto College web-based system, and may include CDs and audio/video streaming. On-campus testing, orientation, and/or other activities may be required.

Online/Classroom (OLC)
Content delivered through an even distribution (50 percent-50 percent) of web-based and classroom activities. These courses use components of computer instruction using the San Jacinto College web-based system, Blackboard, in addition to multimedia activities, and classroom time. On-Campus classroom time is required.

Step 4: It is time to start your semester. Log into the SJC Blackboard system on the first day of class and check your course for communication from your instructor to learn their expectations and get started on assignments.
If you need help, don’t worry, we’ve got you covered via our Distance Learning Support Services.

More information on distance learning support services can be found here: Student Technology Quick Start Guide

values.text:
San Jacinto College is proud to partner with Pasadena ISD and Good Reason Houston to assist graduating Seniors from Dobie High School, Sam Rayburn High School, and South Houston High School pay for college at San Jacinto. The Harris County Promise program is available to Texas resident seniors, regardless of high school GPA or income. Eligible seniors who become Promise Scholars receive up to three years of guaranteed tuition and fees, assistance with books, and additional support to help them complete their degrees.

Harris County Promise is more than a scholarship! It is a community investment designed to provide unparalleled access to higher education. The goal of Harris County Promise is to increase the number of students in our community earning a postsecondary credential by eliminating financial barriers, increasing support, and aligning resources.

Instructions for Scheduling an Online Tutoring Appointment
• Login to TutorTrac at http://sjctutortrac.sanjac.edu/ using your G# and password.
• Choose “Search Availability”: Select the Campus to search for tutor appointments.
• Enter Criteria to search for an available tutor:
• You do not have to choose a consultant. You can just select which class you would like help with and search based on the date and time when you would like help.
• Choose the time when you would like to work with a tutor and save the appointment.
• After your appointments have been scheduled, you will see those appointments from the main screen on TutorTrac.
• When you log back in for the appointment, up to 15 minutes before the appointment starts, you will have a link to join the online session.

Flex Campus

This unique course option will allow you to spend some time in the classroom with your instructor, in addition to online learning. Small groups of students in each class will have the option to attend in person while the remaining students access coursework online. The small groups will rotate so all students in a class have multiple chances to attend in person, although it’s never required when it’s your turn.

The Accuplacer ESL as a Second Language (ESL) tests are computer-adaptive tests intended for use in placing nonnative speakers of English into ESOL courses. ACCUPLACER ESL tests include ESL Reading Skills, ESL Sentence Meaning, ESL Language Use, and ESL Listening. Each test requires test takers to answer 20 items.

Please click the link to learn more about the Accuplacer ESO tests and the test schedule: Accuplacer ESL

Each campus allows walk-in testing for the Accuplacer ESL test. You will need to see an Admissions Advisor to obtain a Testing Request Form and you can bring the form along with your photo identification card to start testing.

We help students facing all types of challenges, such as learning disabilities, visual and hearing impairment, communication disorders, mobility issues, head injuries, chronic illness, and ADD. San Jacinto College awards college credit for certain CLEP exams.

The College-Level Examination Program® (CLEP) offers students the opportunity to receive college credit for what they already know.
• Most exams are timed at 90-minutes except for the College Composition exam (2 hours).
• The cost of each CLEP exam is $87 each and there is also a $20 administrative fee (non-refundable) assessed for each test date.
• There is a $10 fee for all test takers that are taking an optional essay.

For more information about registering for CLEP, including which CLEP exams are offered, click: CLEP Information

values.text:
If you have submitted documents to the Financial Aid Office, you can check the status through SOS under the "My Financial Aid" section. Please note, if you are submitting documents during peak periods (such as registration) processing time on your file may take 3-5 weeks.

Here is how you can read the statuses in SOS:
• "Received, Not Yet Reviewed" - your document has been received and electronically forwarded to the district office for processing, but it has not yet been reviewed
• "Satisfied" - the requirement has been reviewed and satisfied
• "Incomplete" - something submitted is considered incomplete, requiring you to speak with the Financial Aid office about what is still needed
• "Temporary" - your file has been reviewed and has been sent back to the Department of Education for update in their system

values.text:
The HESI A2 entrance exam is required for all students applying to either the Radiography or Registered Nurse programs.

HESI Registration Information
• The HESI A2 exam is only available to San Jacinto College students (Note: The test is ONLY administered at San Jacinto College Central Testing Center)
• To register, you must go to https://www.registerblast.com/sjccentral/exam/list to select a test date and time. You must create an user account to register for the exam. There will be no on campus registration at the Testing Center.
• There is a 14 day waiting period for scheduling an additional HESI test date
• The HESI test fee must be paid online on test day (payment must be debit or credit card, no cash)
• Seating is limited for all test dates. Registration is on a first come first serve basis
• If you need to cancel your test date, you can log into your RegisterBlast account to cancel your registration

For more information about the HESI A2 Entrance Exam, including general test information, preparation, how to retrieve HESI test results, and what to bring on test date, please click the appropriate link:
HESI A2 - Radiography Information
HESI A2 - RN Information

values.text:
If you are a first-time college student, please request that your high school send an official transcript to San Jacinto College.

If you are a returning or transfer college student, you will need to submit an official transcript from each college or university you’ve attended.

University students who hold a degree (associate, bachelor’s, master's or doctoral) only need to submit an official transcript from the school that awarded the highest degree. Students who took additional classes after earning a degree will need a transcript from that college or university as well

Please Note: If you're applying for Financial Aid, all transcripts will be required.

dialog_nodes.title: Diplomas Information

values.text:
After the commencement, degrees should be posted to your official San Jacinto College transcript within 2-3 weeks of the end of the term. An email will be sent when diplomas have been mailed, usually within 2-4 weeks of degrees being posted to your transcript. Diplomas will not be issued to students with financial holds.

Diplomas are mailed to new graduates through USPS to the diploma address specified during the graduation application process. Diplomas for graduates who did not specify an address in the graduation application are sent to the permanent address on file. If you have graduated in the last 3 months and have not received your diploma, please email: educational.planning\@sjcd.edu.

Reprint of an awarded Diploma/Certificate: A diploma reprint request can be made by logging into your San Jac 365 email account, and filling out the Online Order Form. Requests for more than one reprint will result in a five dollar reprint fee per copy. Please note: All duplicate diplomas/certificates will have the signature of the current Chancellor and Board Chair and will use the current diploma template.

International Admissions Steps

You're just a few short steps from becoming a student at San Jacinto College. As a top 10 ranked Community College in the US, we know every student's story is different and welcome students with a variety of different paths they wish to pursue. We've broken down the steps you must take according to which category you fall into here.

Please click here to see a list of frequently asked international student questions.

Form I-20

This is the form San Jacinto College gives you when you’ve completed all your requirements for admission. Keep this with you at all times, even when you leave the U.S. temporarily. It serves as validation of your student status and shows all permissions granted to you, such as transfers, employment, and reentry to the U.S.

International Tuition & Fees

San Jacinto College is supported by local and state tax dollars, which allows us to keep costs low for our students. Here is an estimate of what it might cost an international student to attend San Jac for one year:

Fall and Spring International Student
Tuition/fees- \$5,784
Books/Transportation/Insurance- \$3,900
Living Expenses- \$13,800
Total = \$23,484

Please click here to see more information on San Jacinto College tuition.

Please click here to see more information on working in the United States while you’re going to San Jacinto College.

Applying for and receiving aid all breaks down into these very simple steps:

Step 1- Apply for admission to San Jac. Click Here To Apply

Step 2- Submit your free application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA). You’ll need the San Jacinto College school code, 003609, and an FSA ID* to sign your FAFSA Application.

Step 3- Submit your documentation. We may need copies of official documents to complete the process. If requested, be sure to respond promptly. Please note, if you are submitting documents during peak periods (such as registration) processing time on your file may take 3-5 weeks. Please visit our Forms Menu for a listing of documents that may be requested:
2019-2020 Forms
2020-2021 Forms

For more information, please visit our website at www.sanjac.edu/financial-aid .

An eccentric philosophy professor gave a one question final exam after a semester dealing with a broad array of topics. The class was already seated and ready to go when the professor picked up his chair, plopped it on his desk and wrote on the board: "Using everything we have learned this semester, prove that this chair does not exist."

Fingers flew, erasers erased, notebooks were filled in furious fashion. Some students wrote over 30 pages in one hour attempting to refute the existence of the chair. One member of the class however, was up and finished in less than a minute.

Weeks later when the grades were posted, the rest of the group wondered how he could have gotten an A when he had barely written anything at all. His answer consisted of two words: "What chair?"

College student: "Hey, Dad -- I've got some great news for you!"

Father: "What, son?"

College student: "Remember that \$500 you promised me if I made the Dean's list?"

Father: "I certainly do."

College student: "Well, you get to keep it!"

Professor: "Why do pimples make horrible prisoners?"

Student: "Because they keep breaking out!"

A kid called up his mom from his college and asked her for some money, because he ran out of it. His mom said, "Sure, sweetie. I'll will send you some money. You also left your calculus book here when you visited 2 weeks ago. Do you want me to send that up too?"

"Uhh, oh yeah, okay," responded the kid. So his mom wrapped the book along with the checks up in a package and went to the post office to mail the money and the book.

When she gets back, her husband asked, "Well how much did you give the boy this time?"

She said, "Oh, I wrote two checks, one for \$20 and the other for \$1000 out to him."

"That's \$1020!" yelled her husband. "Are you crazy?"

"Don't worry, Hon," she said. "I taped the \$20 check to the cover of his book, but I put the \$1000 one somewhere between the pages in chapter 19!"

It had been snowing for hours when an announcement came over the University's intercom: "Will the students who are parked on University Drive please move their cars so that we may begin plowing."

Twenty minutes later there was another announcement: "Will the twelve hundred students who went to move 26 cars please return to class."

Math Teacher: "Bob has 36 candy bars. He eats 29. What does he have now?"

Student: "Diabetes"

Science Teacher: "Who can tell me about the first and second Laws of Thermodynamics?">

Student: "First rule of thermodynamcis is you do not talk about thermodynamics. The second rule of thermodynamics is you do not talk about thermodynamics."

What did the DNA say to the other DNA?

"Do these genes make me look fat?"

Why did Beethoven get rid of his chickens?
All they said was "Bach, Bach, Bach..."

The Financial Aid Academic Progress Statuses are:
• "Warning" - You are not meeting the GPA or pass rate standards. This of this as a 'head-up', a way of letting you know what you need to do.
• "Suspension" - You are no longer eligible to receive Financial Aid
• "Maximum Time Frame" - you have attempted more than 90 hours (including transfer hours) and are no longer eligible to receive aid
• "Probation" - You failed to make satisfactory academic progress and you have appealed to have your financial aid reinstated, placing you in probation for one term

values.text:
This could require more documentation for some and less for others. Once your appeal is received with all appropriate documentation and reviewed by the financial aid office, the Financial Aid Appeals Committee will meet to review it. You will be notified of the decision via e-mail within two weeks after the committee reviews your appeal. Failure to provide the required documentation, a completed FAFSA, and the completed special circumstance appeal form could cause your appeal to be denied. Please be prepared to pay for your registration expenses (tuition, fees, books and supplies) since your appeal might not be reviewed prior to the payment deadline.

Please Note: We are required to review personal details in reference to your special circumstance. Some of this information may be very sensitive in nature, but we are required to review it to make a decision. Any information you provide will be kept confidential.

values.text:
Any classes removed while on a payment plan will be deducted from remaining payments based on the refund periods listed on the links below:
Fall 2020 Refund Dates
Spring 2021 Refund Dates

If you happen to withdraw from any classes, payments are still due on time. If any refunds apply, we will simply recalculate what you owe and the changes will be reflected on your future installments. For example, if you drop a class at a 70% refund, 70% of the charges are removed and you must pay the remaining 30%. If you drop classes at a 0% refund, no charges are removed.

values.text: It’s never too late to begin the journey toward accomplishing your goals! San Jacinto College Testing Centers offers two tests for students to attain a certificate of high school equivalency for the state of Texas - the Pearson General Educational Development (GED) and the ETS High School Equivalency Test (HiSET). Each test is available in English and Spanish. Just In case you are wondering, San Jacinto College does also accept GED and HiSET as acceptable high school equivalency diplomas.

generic.title: Would you like more information on high school equivalency exams?

values.text:
You must schedule your exam through the official GED website. You will be able to view more information, such as such as test eligibility requirements, test date availability, contact information, and schedule an appointment to take the GED test by using the following link: Pearson GED

To schedule your GED exam:
• Simply create/ log into your MyGED® : Login
• Choose which test subjects you’ll be taking.
• Select a day and time at an official GED® test center near you. Please note: To test at San Jacinto College, you must select San Jacinto College as your test center upon GED registration. GED Test Center Search
• Pay for the test online using a credit or debit card.

When you are ready to test, you will need to bring the following items to the selected San Jacinto College Testing Center in order to be seated on your scheduled test day:
• Your photo identification card (must be valid and government issued)
• Proof of Texas residency (if not shown on your photo ID)

dialog_nodes.title: Course Number Information

values.text:
Reading a Course Number

The first digit of the course number indicates the level of the course.
• 1 = freshman course
• 2 = sophomore course
The second digit of the course number indiates the credit in semester hours.
The third and fourth digits of the course number indicates the sequence of a course in a group of similar courses.

Example: ENGL 1302 is a freshman course (1) that is worth 3 credit hours (3) that is normally taken as the second (02) of the series of freshman writing courses.

For more information regarding reading course numbers, visit our website at Class Schedule Numbering.

dialog_nodes.user_label: How do I read a course number?

dialog_nodes.title: Room Number Information

values.text:
Reading a Room Number

The first character (letter) of the room number indicates the campus location.
• C = Central Campus • M = Maritime Campus
• N = North Campus • G = Generation Park Campus
• S = South Campus
The second grouping of characters (numbers in front of the period) indicate the building location.
The remaining characters behind the period indicate the actual room number. (Note: The very first number will indicate the floor of the building)

Example: The Financial Aid Office at the Central Campus is located at C-27.1300.
• C = Central Campus
• 27 = Building 27 (Welcome Center)
• 1300 = Specific room/suite number 1300 located on the first floor

dialog_nodes.user_label: What is FERPA?

values.text:
The Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act of 1974 (FERPA) helps protect the privacy of student education records. Students have the right to: • be notified of their FERPA rights at least once annually
• inspect and review their records
• amend an incorrect record
• consent to disclosure (with exceptions)

values.text:
Prerequisites & Co-requisites

A Prerequisite is a course that provides the basic skill levels of knowledge you will need before you can enroll into the next more advanced course, as defined by Texas Success Initiative.

A Co-requisite is a course that you have to take at the same time as, or before, another course before you can enroll into the next more advanced course, as defined by Texas Success Initiative.

All prerequisites and co-requisites on course enrollment are strictly enforced at the time of the student’s registration. Course descriptions in the catalog will indicate which courses have such prerequisites to help you choose courses that best fit your degree plan, career goals, and/or transfer requirements.

Please click HERE to view prerequisites and co-requisites for courses.

generic.title: Would you like information on Prerequisite or Co-requisite Waivers?

values.text:
Prerequisite & Co-requisite Waivers

Under special circumstances, the department may allow a student to register for a course without the required prerequisite or co-requisite. A waiver of the required prerequisite or co-requisite does not affect degree requirements. Students who have been granted a waiver may earn needed credit through course substitution or credit by examination. Although students may receive credit toward graduation at San Jacinto College, if prerequisites are waived for certain courses, another college may not allow credit for such courses. If students do not follow prerequisite/co-requisite requirements, the College may withdraw them from the course.

values.text:
Great! Do you desire an advanced practice or leadership position in nursing? Do you want higher-level skills to respond better to the demands of today’s evolving healthcare system? If so, San Jacinto College’s Bachelor of Science in Nursing (RN-to-BSN) program may be perfect for you!

The one-year BSN program is for the working registered nurse (RN with an associate degree) who wants to advance within the profession. The program can be completed in three consecutive semesters and follows an eight-week course model, building on previous education and experience while providing face-to-face and distance learning opportunities that accommodate an employed RN’s schedule.

values:
Honors Program Eligibility:

1. Continuing SJC students, transfer students and Dual Credit/Early College High School/MECA students with at least 12 college credit hours and a 3.25 cumulative GPA or students who are members of PTK or NSCS are eligible to apply for admission to the SJC Honors Program.
2. First-Time-In-College (FTIC) students, Dual Credit/Early College High School/MECA/Home-schooled students with fewer than 12 college credit hours who meet one of the following documented criteria are eligible to apply for admission to the SJC Honors Program:
• 3.25+ accredited high school GPA
• Score of 4 or 5 on an Advanced Placement (AP) exam
• Top 20% of high school graduating class
• Minimum SAT score of 1160 (ie., critical reading and math combined)
• Minimum ACT score of 26
3. Returning or non-traditional students who have completed at least 12 college credit hours in the previous five years with a 3.25+ cumulative GPA for the most recent 12 college credit hours are eligible to apply for admissions to the SJC Honors Program. Returning or non-traditional students who have not completed at least 12 college credit hours in the past five years are encouraged to do so before applying.
4. Approval by campus coordinator.

If you would like to submit an online application for the Honors Program, click http://sjc.prod.acquia-sites.com/form/honors-program-admission-application

Probation

If you failed to make satisfactory academic progress and you have appealed to have your financial aid reinstated, you are placed on Probation for one term. You are required to meet the conditions stated on your appeal approval contract without exception.

values.text:
There are 3 steps for Previous or Returning Financial Aid Appeals

Step 1: Scheduled appeal appointment
Step 2: Gather requested appeal documents
Step 3: Submit required documentation for appeal committee review

Note: Due to the current campus closures, please click here to schedule a time to meet with an advisor remotely.

generic.title: Would you like more detailed information on the required steps for Previous or Returning Financial Aid Appeals?

values:
Step 1: Scheduled appeal appointment

Visit or speak with a financial aid representative at your campus Financial Aid Office to obtain appeal paperwork and discuss needed appeal documents. Please note: documents needed will vary on a case by case basis. You must see an advisor to determine what documents are needed for your specific appeal case. You must have all requested documents at the time you submit your appeal for review.

Appeals appointments are accepted Monday-Thursday, 10 a.m. – 3 p.m.*and Friday, 9-11 a.m.*

*If you need an appointment outside of this time, please contact the Financial Aid Office.

values.text: If it is not your first time to submit a financial aid appeal, your packet will be collected and forwarded to the appeal committee for further review. If your written appeal is denied by an advisor or the committee, you have the option to request a personal appearance with the appeal committee.

generic.title: Would you like additional information about requesting a personal appearance with the appeal committee?

values:
Step 3: Maintain Financial Aid Appeal Contract Requirements

As stated in your appeal contract, while on financial aid appeal, your conditions are as follows:
• Pass all classes with a minimum of letter grade “C”.
• You may not withdraw or drop courses while on financial aid appeal
• You may not change your major, or take courses not listed on the degree plan filed with the financial aid appeal
• Complete literacy and coaching Program for Financial Education (PFE) component

values.text:
If you have any unusual or extenuating circumstances that you feel are not reflected on your financial aid application, please come in person to the financial aid office. The Financial Aid Office will review your circumstance and determine whether you meet the conditions to submit such an appeal. Students must be able to provide official documentation that demonstrates the unusual circumstances.

Because each situation is unique, special circumstance appeals are processed on a case-by-case basis.

generic.title: Would you like more information regarding Special Circumstance Appeal?

The ESOL program is designed for international, residential and non-residential students who want to improve their English. Students can complete the program in one academic year (nine months) and are prepared for college and university admission exams, such as the Texas Success Initiative Assessment (TSIA) or Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL). The curriculum covers language skills in oral communication; grammar, reading and writing for the workplace; and college career or university studies. Courses are taught by master teachers with lecture, group projects and computer assignments. A Certificate of Completion is awarded upon ESOL program completion.

Please click here for more information on the ESOL program.

values.text:
TASFA stands for the Texas Application for State Financial Aid. Students that are classified as a Texas Resident, and went to high school for at least three years in the state who cannot apply for federal financial aid using the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) are encouraged to complete the TASFA. These include, but are not limited to, foreign nationals, legal permanent residents, and eligible non-citizens. You can only apply for either FAFSA or TASFA, not both.

To apply for TASFA, please stop by your local San Jac Financial Aid Office to request an application. The TASFA is a paper application and must be printed, filled out, signed, and submitted at your local San Jac Financial Aid Office with all applicable documents by the deadline in order to be reviewed for potential funding.

To learn more about eligibility requirements, visit College for All Texans .

Attendance Policy - Part 4 of 4

An instructor also has the authority to request that the student drop the course and to prohibit a student from participating in class when the instructor believes the student has accumulated so many absences (including excused absences) that the student cannot reasonably expect to pass the course. An instructor may also award the temporary grade of I (Incomplete) only under certain circumstances. Students may see the Incomplete (I) section under the Grading System section for specific information.

Please Note: A student who wishes to withdraw from a course must withdraw oﬃcially online or through the Educational Planning, Counseling, & Completion oﬃce; informing the instructor of the intent to withdraw is not sufficient. The Withdrawal from Courses section that follows provides more information.

Accreditation or certification standards that require more stringent attendance policies may govern certain departments or programs. College regulations specify that only students who have registered for the class and who are listed on the official class rolls may attend a class. Students not listed on official class rolls may not attend classes; nor may students who have withdrawn or who have been withdrawn attend classes.

dialog_nodes.title: Application for Graduation

values.text:
To apply for graduation, please follow these simple steps:

Do a Graduation Status Check. Log into SOS and go to Student Records, run a degree evaluation and print it out. Write in notes next to requirements that are currently in progress or pending, and bring the form to the EPCC office on the campus where you would like to graduate by the deadline listed in the class schedule.

Once the EPCC office verifies that you are eligible to graduate, you will be provided an application for your degree or certificate. Be sure to inform us whether you'd like to attend your graduation ceremony. If you do, be sure to order your cap and gown through one of the campus bookstores.

4. Register for classes.
o Students must visit the Dual Credit office in person to register. Web registration is NOT available for dual credit students. To register, complete a Dual Credit/Early Admission Enrollment Form with your high school counselor. The form must indicate the college classes that you need to take and be signed by the student, parent, and high school counselor or designee
o Turn the completed, signed, form in to the San Jac Dual Credit Office or your high school counselor.
o To speed up the registration process, you can view a list of available courses by searching our Course Finder.

5. Pay for Classes.
Dual Credit at San Jacinto College is affordable. You pay only 25% of tuition and fees for certain classes that count toward both high school and college, and you may even be covered for that amount if you qualify for the Texas Public Education Grant (TPEG). Check with your high school counselor, the Dual Credit Office, or SJC Financial Aid for more information.
o To remain in your classes, you must pay your portion of tuition and fees by the college's posted deadline. Some schools cover these costs for students. Check with your counselor for further information.
o Once a student has been registered, they will be given the 75% fee waiver if applicable to be taken to the Business Office. The remaining balance is due immediately to avoid being dropped from classes. Payment Plans are available.
o Financial Aid - If you're in high school and enroll in dual credit classes, you may apply for a TPEG to cover your share of the tuition and fees. You must complete the TASFA or a paper version of the FAFSA and submit income documents along with your TPEG dual credit application at one of our campus Financial Aid Offices

values.text:
Credit by Examination

Please Note: Each college and university has its own policy for credit earned by examination and any such credit allowed by one institution may not necessarily be accepted at another.

A student must have earned at least three credit hours of course work at San Jacinto College before the College will post credit for College Level Evaluation Program (CLEP), Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate (IB) or departmental examinations to the student’s transcript. Credit for CLEP, AP, IB, departmental examinations or a combination thereof may not exceed 30 credit hours.

A student who has previously received a grade (A, B, C, D, F or I) in a course may not receive CLEP, AP, IB, or departmental examination credit for the same course. Grades and credit hours are assigned to credit earned by departmental examinations; a minimum grade of C is required to earn credit. Term hours only are assigned to credit earned by CLEP, AP, and IB examinations. Residence credit is not given for CLEP, AP, IB or departmental examinations and they are not included in GPA calculations.

values.text:
If you have received a grade of FX, this means that you have failed the course due to missing an excessive number of absences. The grade of FX carries the same academic impact as the grade of F in that credit hours are included in the calculation of the grade point average and the grade awards zero (0) grade points.

You may process to appeal the grade of FX just as you would for any other faculty-awarded grade.

About CPD

Sure! From customized corporate training, to personal enrichment, to workforce development, San Jacinto College has affordable solutions to help you do the following:

Enhance Your Job Skills
The workforce area of the division offers courses that keep workers up to date on the latest technologies in industries such as petrochemical, manufacturing, health care, aerospace and maritime. These courses are available through contract training, open enrollment and grant funding.

Learn for Fun
Not only does the division provide vital training for workers, many participants find enjoyment by picking up new skills they've been eager to learn. CPD also offers lifelong learning courses that offer people a variety of affordable lessons in areas such as dance, martial arts, scrapbooking, retirement and motorcycle riding. More than 40 course options have been developed for the purpose of leisure learning and to help people expand their horizons.

values.text: Great! A helpful website that I can recommend if you are wishing to transfer credit from or to a Texas Institution is The Texas Common Course Numbering System (TCCNS). The Texas Common Course Numbering System (TCCNS) is a voluntary, co-operative effort among 137 Texas community colleges and universities to facilitate transfer of freshman and sophomore level general academic coursework. TCCNS provides a shared, uniform set of course designations for students and their advisors to use in determining both course equivalency and degree applicability of transfer credit on a statewide basis.

Attendance Policy Information

values.text: Okay, let me help you with attendance information. Your instructor determines and outlines at the start of the class how many absences they will allow in their course. Please contact your instructor if you need further explanation of the attendance policy. You can check the course syllabus for the absence policy & contact info for your instructor.

generic.title: Do you need more information on the San Jac attendance policy?

dialog_nodes.user_label: What is San Jac's attendance policy?

values.text:
Attendance Policy - Part 2 of 4

Because an education is more than just acquiring information, students must attend all lecture and laboratory periods. Through regular class attendance, students gain clearer insight into complex issues through interaction with instructors and other students. Instructors keep an accurate record of each student’s attendance and do not allow students who do not attend regularly to slow the pace of the class.

However, instructors may provide an opportunity for a student who presents a reasonable excuse for an absence to make up missed work. A student who does not offer a satisfactory explanation for an absence will have that absence classified as unexcused and earn an F for any test, assignment or laboratory work given or due during that absence. The student will not be allowed to make up work that was missed.

dialog_nodes.title: Enrollment Status Information

values.text:
Okay, let’s get started with that information. Your enrollment status is determined by the number of semester hours you’re taking at San Jacinto College for a given semester.
• Full-time 12 or more hours
• Three-quarter time 9-11 hours
• Half-time 6-8 hours
• Less than half-time 1-5 hours

Please Note: These hours exclude audit courses, transfer work, credit by exam, and Continuing and Professional Development classes.

The second digit of the course number indicates the credit hours associated with that course. Simply calculate the total for all of your courses for the semester to determine your enrollment status.

generic.title: Would you like to learn about the maximum course loads allowed for each semester?

dialog_nodes.user_label: What is my enrollment status?

values.text:
Maximum Course Loads
• The maximum course load permitted in a 16-week term is 18 term hours of credit.
• The maximum course load permitted during the summer term is 14 term hours (or 7 term hours per summer five-week part of term).
• The maximum course load permitted in a three-week mini session is 3 term hours.

Note: Only with the approval of the instructional Dean, students may enroll in additional term hours of credit.

Attendance Policy - Part 3 of 4

Okay, let’s continue with more information. Whenever a student’s absences reach 8.33 percent of the contact hours of the course for unexcused reasons or reasons unknown to the instructor, the instructor may request that the student drop the course (if applicable, students may see TEC 51.907 Six-Drop Limit Provisions section) and if not eligible to drop or the student chooses not to drop, the instructor may award a grade of FX at that time, which will prohibit the student from attending class.

For example, the number of contact hours in a fall or spring term course equals the number of weekly classroom and laboratory hours in the course description multiplied by 16. Therefore, instructors may prohibit the students who accumulate four hours of absence in classes meeting three hours per week or eight hours of absence in classes meeting six hours per week from attending class. Three unexcused tardies count as one unexcused absence.
